---
import Layout from "../../layouts/Layout.astro";
import Navigation from "../../components/Navigation.astro";
import Footer from "../../components/Footer.astro";
---

<Layout title="HisabProx Case Study">
  <Navigation />

  <main id="main-content" class="flex-1 max-w-[68ch] mx-auto px-6 py-16 sm:py-24 flex flex-col gap-12 font-sans">
    
    <!-- Header -->
    <header class="flex flex-col gap-4">
      <div class="flex gap-2 text-xs text-[#71717A] font-mono">
        <span>Work</span>
        <span>·</span>
        <span>Case Study</span>
      </div>
      <h1 class="text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-display font-medium text-[#FAFAFA] tracking-tight leading-tight">
        HisabProx: Building a Local-First Invoice Compiler
      </h1>
      <p class="text-sm text-[#A1A1AA] italic">
        A case study on browser-only persistence, local PDF compilation, and data privacy principles.
      </p>
    </header>

    <!-- Case Study Content -->
    <div class="flex flex-col gap-12 text-[#FAFAFA] text-base leading-[1.7] tracking-tight font-normal">
      
      <!-- Overview -->
      <section class="flex flex-col gap-3">
        <h2 class="text-xs text-[#71717A] uppercase tracking-wider font-semibold">Overview</h2>
        <p>
          HisabProx is an invoice compiler utility built for independent developers and freelancers.
          Rather than relying on central cloud hosting accounts that store business billing information,
          HisabProx operates entirely within the browser sandboxed environment.
          This study covers the local-first principles, state structure, and PDF compilation mechanisms.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Problem -->
      <section class="flex flex-col gap-3">
        <h2 class="text-xs text-[#71717A] uppercase tracking-wider font-semibold">Problem</h2>
        <p>
          Modern invoice editors are almost universally subscription-based SaaS tools.
          They require user accounts, collect detailed financial transactional histories of clients, and require active internet connections.
          For freelancers who value client confidentiality and data ownership,
          cloud-based invoicing exposes sensitive operations to third-party data breaches.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Approach -->
      <section class="flex flex-col gap-3">
        <h2 class="text-xs text-[#71717A] uppercase tracking-wider font-semibold">Approach</h2>
        <p>
          I wanted to create an editor that could run offline indefinitely, require zero user setup, and collect zero tracking data.
          The user interface had to be responsive, distraction-free, and focus on fast data entry.
          The central constraint was that all information must reside in the user's browser, preventing external leaks.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Architecture -->
      <section class="flex flex-col gap-3">
        <h2 class="text-xs text-[#71717A] uppercase tracking-wider font-semibold">Architecture</h2>
        <p>
          HisabProx is built as a single-page React application written in TypeScript.
          For styling, it uses Tailwind CSS to structure clean, high-contrast layouts.
          Client-side persistence is handled by the browser local storage API,
          retaining invoice entries, client metadata profiles, and configuration settings locally.
        </p>
        <p>
          To generate professional PDF documents without using a backend server,
          the application compiles invoice layout structures directly in the browser thread using PDFKit.
          This client-side PDF compiler outputs raw binary buffers that the browser downloads directly,
          ensuring billing documents are generated securely.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Trade-offs -->
      <section class="flex flex-col gap-3">
        <h2 class="text-xs text-[#71717A] uppercase tracking-wider font-semibold">Trade-offs</h2>
        <p>
          Building a browser-only tool prevents automatic multi-device synchronization.
          If a user switches laptops, their invoice history is not immediately available.
          To address this limitation without compromising privacy,
          I designed a backup system that lets users manually export and import encrypted JSON snapshots of their settings.
        </p>
        <p>
          Additionally, local storage is subject to browser-clearing events.
          We prioritized absolute client privacy and zero server maintenance overhead
          at the expense of managed server-side backups.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- What Failed (The Biggest Mistake) -->
      <section class="flex flex-col gap-3">
        <h2 class="text-xs text-[#71717A] uppercase tracking-wider font-semibold">What Failed</h2>
        <p>
          I initially built a database synchronization service using a third-party cloud connector.
          This required managing user authentication states, securing remote endpoints, and paying database hosting bills.
          It conflicted with the core design goal of data privacy and added unnecessary operational complexity.
          I chose to delete the sync backend entirely to return the tool to a true, offline-only utility.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Lessons -->
      <section class="flex flex-col gap-3">
        <h2 class="text-xs text-[#71717A] uppercase tracking-wider font-semibold">Lessons</h2>
        <p>
          Modern client browsers are fully capable of processing layouts, compiling binaries, and retaining state.
          Avoiding servers not only guarantees data security but also eliminates hosting bills and service maintenance.
          Local-first architectures are incredibly durable and remain functional as long as the browser exists.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Links / GitHub -->
      <section class="flex flex-col gap-3 border-t border-[rgba(255,255,255,0.06)] pt-6">
        <h2 class="text-xs text-[#71717A] uppercase tracking-wider font-semibold">Source Code</h2>
        <div class="flex items-center gap-4 text-xs font-mono">
          <a href="https://github.com/programmer-nick234/hisabprox" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-[#2563EB] hover:underline">
            GitHub Repository
          </a>
        </div>
      </section>

    </div>

    <!-- Tech Stack footer -->
    <footer class="flex flex-col gap-6 border-t border-[rgba(255,255,255,0.08)] pt-8 mt-4 text-xs font-mono text-[#71717A]">
      <span>Technologies: TypeScript · React · Local Storage · PDFKit · Tailwind CSS</span>
    </footer>

  </main>

  <Footer />
</Layout>
